Project idea

Border Wait Checker

A small Python app that checks Poland to Ukraine border crossing wait times and shows them in a clean, useful way.

The point is simple:
	•	fetch border data
	•	extract the useful parts
	•	clean it up
	•	compare crossings
	•	show the best option fast

⸻

What the project does

You run the app and it:
	1.	connects to a border wait time source
	2.	downloads the latest page or data
	3.	finds the crossing names and queue times
	4.	cleans the text into readable values
	5.	sorts or highlights the shortest wait
	6.	prints a simple summary

Later you can expand it to:
	•	filter only Poland to Ukraine crossings
	•	save last checked results
	•	compare car vs truck queues
	•	alert when a crossing drops below a set wait time

⸻

Project structure

Keep it split into small functions, each with one job.

Main flow

Your main script should feel like this:

def run():
    raw_data = fetch_data()
    border_rows = extract_border_rows(raw_data)
    clean_data = parse_wait_times(border_rows)
    show_results(clean_data)

That is clean. That is readable. That is maintainable.

⸻

Core functions

1. fetch_data()

Purpose: Get the webpage or source data.

What it does:
	•	sends request to the border site
	•	returns raw HTML or raw text

Input:
	•	none, or later maybe a URL

Output:
	•	raw page content

⸻

2. extract_border_rows(raw_data)

Purpose: Pull out only the relevant border rows from the full page.

What it does:
	•	scans the HTML
	•	finds table rows or sections containing border info
	•	ignores junk like headers, menus, adverts

Input:
	•	raw HTML/text

Output:
	•	a list of border rows

⸻

3. parse_wait_times(border_rows)

Purpose: Turn messy text into structured data.

What it does:
	•	reads each row
	•	extracts crossing name
	•	extracts wait time
	•	stores it in a useful format

Input:
	•	list of raw rows

Output:
	•	list of dictionaries like:

[
    {"crossing": "Zosin", "wait": "2 hours"},
    {"crossing": "Dorohusk", "wait": "5 hours"}
]

Better still, convert wait into numbers:

[
    {"crossing": "Zosin", "wait_hours": 2},
    {"crossing": "Dorohusk", "wait_hours": 5}
]

That gives you something you can sort properly.

⸻

4. show_results(clean_data)

Purpose: Display the information clearly.

What it does:
	•	prints each crossing and its wait
	•	highlights the shortest queue
	•	maybe sorts shortest to longest

Input:
	•	cleaned structured list

Output:
	•	printed report for the user

Example output:

BORDER WAIT TIMES

1. Zosin        2 hours
2. Hrebenne     3 hours
3. Dorohusk     5 hours

Fastest crossing: Zosin


⸻

Optional support functions

These are not required at first, but they make the project stronger.

5. sort_by_wait(clean_data)

Purpose: Sort crossings from shortest to longest.

6. filter_crossings(clean_data, names)

Purpose: Show only crossings you care about.

Example:
	•	Zosin
	•	Dorohusk
	•	Hrebenne
	•	Korczowa

7. save_results(clean_data)

Purpose: Save results to a file so you can compare later.

Could save to:
	•	text file
	•	csv file
	•	json file

8. load_previous_results()

Purpose: Show the last saved check.

Useful if internet drops.

